== Reception == Despite the controversial and polarizing nature of the material, the reviews have largely been positive. ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised Sandel's ability to teach and says, "If 'Justice' breaks no new philosophical ground, it succeeds at something perhaps no less important: in terms we can all understand, it confronts us with the concepts that lurk, so often unacknowledged, beneath our conflicts."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/29/books/review/Rauch-t.html|title=Book Review {{!}} 'Justice: What’s the Right Thing to Do?,' by Michael J. Sandel|last=Rauch|first=Jonathan|date=2009-11-27|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-11-03|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' calls it a "timely plea for us to desist from political bickering and see if we can have a sensible discussion about what sort of society we really want to live in."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/nov/01/justice-michael-sandel|title=Justice: What's the Right Thing to Do? by Michael Sandel {{!}} Book review|last=Reé|first=Jonathan|date=2009-11-01|work=The Observer|access-date=2017-11-03|language=en-GB|issn=0029-7712}}</ref> ''The Portsmouth Review'' calls it an "enlightening read".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://portsmouthreview.com/justice-whats-the-right-thing-to-do-by-michael-j-sandel-book-review/|title=Justice: What's the Right Thing to Do? by Michael J. Sandel Book Review {{!}} The Portsmouth Review|last=Skane|first=Rebecca|date=2017-09-25|work=The Portsmouth Review|access-date=2017-11-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130051545/https://portsmouthreview.com/justice-whats-the-right-thing-to-do-by-michael-j-sandel-book-review/|archive-date=2018-01-30|dead-url=yes|language=en-US}}</ref>
