'''Sir (Paul) Patrick (Gordon) Bateson''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|FRS}} (31 March 1938 &ndash; 1 August 2017) was an [[England|English]] [[biology|biologist]] and science writer.  Bateson was a [[professor]] of [[ethology]] at the [[University of Cambridge]] and president of the [[Zoological Society of London]].<ref>[http://archive.bio.ed.ac.uk/asab/resources/profiles/bateson.html Career profiles: How I came to study animal behaviour]</ref><ref>[http://www.alanmacfarlane.com/ancestors/bateson.htm Patrick Bateson interviewed by Alan Macfarlane 13 December 2007 (film)]</ref><ref name=scopus>{{Scopus id}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zoo.cam.ac.uk/news/professor-sir-patrick-bateson-frs|website=zoo.cam.ac.uk|title=Professor Sir Patrick Bateson, FRS}}</ref>

==Education==
Bateson was educated at [[Westminster School]]<ref name=whoswho/> and [[King's College, Cambridge]]<ref name=whoswho>Anon (2017) {{Who's Who | surname = BATESON | othernames = Prof. Sir (Paul) Patrick (Gordon) | id = U6789 | edition = online [[Oxford University Press]]|location=Oxford}} {{doi|10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.6789}}{{subscription required}}</ref> where he was awarded a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[zoology]]{{when|date=August 2017}} and a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] for research on [[ethology|animal behaviour]] supervised by [[Robert Hinde]].<ref>{{cite thesis|degree=PhD|publisher=University of Cambridge|title=The Development of Filial and Avoidance behaviour in the domestic chicken|first=Paul Patrick Gordon|last=Bateson|date=1963|url=http://copac.jisc.ac.uk/id/23483522?style=html|id={{EThOS|uk.bl.ethos.449192}}|website=copac.jisc.ac.uk|oclc=500380329}}</ref><ref name=nobit/><ref name="Bateson2015">{{cite journal|last1=Bateson|first1=Patrick|title=Patrick Bateson|journal=Current Biology|volume=25|issue=5|year=2015|pages=R180–R181|issn=0960-9822|doi=10.1016/j.cub.2014.12.040|pmid=25897438}}</ref>

==Career and research==
Bateson was a biologist who specialised in researching the behaviour of animals and how it is influenced by genetic and environmental factors. Patrick was a world authority on imprinting in birds — the process of learning to recognise their parents and members of their own species — and his work led to new principles in behavioural development.<ref name=frs>{{cite web|title=Professor Patrick Bateson FRS|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170815135948/https://royalsociety.org/people/patrick-bateson-11050|archivedate=2017-08-15|url=https://royalsociety.org/people/patrick-bateson-11050|website=royalsociety.org|publisher=[[Royal Society]]|location=London|author=Anon|year=2017}}

One or more of the preceding sentences incorporates text from the royalsociety.org website where:{{quote|“All text published under the heading 'Biography' on Fellow profile pages is available under [[Creative Commons license|Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License]].” --{{cite web |url=https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies |title=Royal Society Terms, conditions and policies |accessdate=2017-08-24 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161111170346/https://royalsociety.org/about-us/terms-conditions-policies |archivedate=11 November 2016 |df=dmy-all }}}}</ref>

Bateson devised original experiments that showed how characteristics of imprinting depend on the bird’s early life experiences. Bateson's investigation of learning in birds has led to greater understanding of the neural basis of memory. He had an interest in how developmental and behavioural processes influence evolution.<ref name=frs/>

Bateson was concerned with the ethics of using animals in research and the analysis of animal pain and suffering. This led to a study into the effects on red deer of hunting with hounds, an inquiry into dog breeding and a review of the use of animals in research.<ref name=frs/>

Previous academic positions include a [[Harkness Fellowship]] at [[Stanford University]]<ref name=nobit/><ref>[http://www.edge.org/3rd_culture/bios/batesonp.html Patrick Bateson profile], Edge.org; accessed 18 February 2017.</ref> and ten years as head of the Cambridge sub-department of Animal Behaviour. Bateson retired as the biological secretary to the Royal Society after five years and [[Master (college)|Provost]] of [[King's College, Cambridge]] after fifteen years in 2003. He retired from his Cambridge Chair in 2005.

Bateson published on such topics as ethology, [[animal welfare]], behavioral development and [[evolution]].

