{{Infobox philosopher |region = [[Western philosophy]] |era = [[Contemporary philosophy]] |image = |caption = |name = Thomas Hurka |birth_date = 1952 |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = [[Analytic philosophy]] |main_interests = [[Moral philosophy]] |notable_ideas = [[Perfectionism (philosophy)|Perfectionism]] |influences = [[G. E. Moore]], [[W. D. Ross]], [[Harold Arthur Prichard]] |influenced = |signature = }}
'''Thomas Hurka''' (born 1952) is a Canadian philosopher who holds the Jackman Distinguished Chair in Philosophical Studies at the [[University of Toronto]] and who taught previously, from 1978 to 2002, at the [[University of Calgary]].<ref name=uot>{{cite web|title=Thomas Hurka|url=http://www.philosophy.utoronto.ca/directory/thomas-hurka/|work=Philosophy|publisher=University of Toronto|accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref> He was elected a Fellow of the [[Royal Society of Canada]] in 2001.<ref>http://www.provost.utoronto.ca/awards/uprofessors/complete/hurkat.htm</ref>
Hurka has published works on a number of topics, including the topics of goodness,<ref>{{citation|last=Rønnow-Rasmussen|first=Toni|title=Personal Value|year=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-960378-7|page=96}}</ref> [[virtue]],<ref>{{citation|last=Battaly|first=Heather|title=Virtue and Vice, Moral and Epistemic|year=2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-5193-4|page=75}}</ref> and [[ethics]].<ref>{{citation|last=Govier|first=Trudy|title=A Practical Study of Argument|year=2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=978-0-495-60340-5|page=354}}</ref> His philosophy focuses on the well-rounded life. He cited that goods, which come in four basic categories - pleasure, knowledge, achievement, and virtue - matter more the less of them you have.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=The Quality of Life: Aristotle Revised|last=Kraut|first=Richard|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2018|isbn=9780198828846|location=New York|pages=158}}</ref> In his theory, he stressed that it is more appropriate to seek a balanced variety of them all instead of devoting oneself to one kind.<ref name=":0" /> His conception of virtue is different from the view that an agent ought to maximize their own good, which requires being virtuous. Instead, Hurka stressed that "agents ought to maximize the good of all, which requires conventionally right action, and as a side effect can maximize their own good."<ref>{{Cite book|title=Virtue, Vice, and Value|last=Hurka|first=Thomas|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=2001|isbn=0195137167|location=New York|pages=56}}</ref>
Hurka has also studied the ethics of fighting [[Global Warming]].<ref>{{citation|last=Coward|first=Harold G.|title=Ethics & climate change: the greenhouse effect|page=7|year=1993|publisher=Wilfrid Laurier University Press|isbn=978-0-88920-233-7|authorlink=Harold Coward}}</ref> He maintained that if we reject the notion that individuals should only pursue their own self-interest, then we can assign ethical standing to a wider range of beings besides ourselves.<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|title=Ethical Choices and Global Greenhouse Warming|last=Dotto|first=Lydia|publisher=Wilfrid Laurier University Press|year=2010|isbn=0889202346|location=Ontario|pages=8}}</ref> This is significant in addressing global warming because it morally pushes towards strategies of avoiding instead of adapting to climate change.<ref name=":1" />
He received his DPhil from [[Oxford University]].<ref name=uot/>
